## **Lab 8: Network Policies in Kubernetes for MinIO Deployment**

***Estimated Time; 25 Mins***

#### ***Objective:***

In this lab, Kubernetes administrators will learn how to define and apply Network Policies to control traffic to and from the MinIO pods within a Kubernetes cluster. The lab will cover:

1. Creating a namespace for MinIO deployment.  
2. Deploying MinIO in the namespace.  
3. Defining and applying network policies to restrict access between pods and limit external access.

**Part 1: Minikube setup with CNI**

The default Minikube setup does not include a CNI (Container Network Interface) that supports Network Policies. By default, Minikube uses basic Kubernetes networking, which does not enforce Network Policies unless a proper CNI that supports them is installed.

Network Policies in Kubernetes depend on the underlying CNI plugin to enforce the rules. If a CNI that supports Network Policies is not installed, the policies will have no effect.

| minikube deleteminikube start \--network-plugin\=cni \--cni\=calico |
| :---- |

**Part 2: Deploy MinIO in a namespace**

**Step 1: Create Namespace for MinIO Deployment**

| kubectl create namespace minio-network |
| :---- |

**Step 2: Deploy MinIO StatefulSet in the New Namespace**

YAML file for Minio Statefulset is located at Kubernetes\_Admins/labs/Lab8/minio\_statefulset.yaml

| kubectl apply \-f minio\_statefulset.yaml |
| :---- |

**Step 3: Expose MinIO**

YAML file for service to expose MinIO is located at Kubernetes\_Admins/labs/Lab8/minio\_service.yaml

| kubectl apply \-f minio\_service.yaml |
| :---- |

**Step 4: Verify that MinIO is running:**

| kubectl get pod \-n minio-network |
| :---- |

**Part 3: Test Connectivity without Network Policies**

By default, pods from different namespaces can access the MinIO service in the `minio-network` namespace when no Network Policies are applied.

**Step 1: Create a New Namespace for Testing**

| kubectl create namespace test-namespace |
| :---- |

**Step 2: Run Test Pod**

Let’s run a test pod in the namespace we created in the above step. 

| kubectl run test-pod \--image=appropriate/curl \--labels=app=client \-n test-namespace \--command \-- /bin/sh \-c "sleep 3600" |
| :---- |

**Step 3: Verify Access to MinIO from the Test Pod**:

| kubectl exec \-it test\-pod \-n test\-namespace \-- curl \-u admin:password  http://minio-service.minio-network.svc.cluster.local:9001 |
| :---- |

![][image1]

Did you notice that you got html snippet that is actually a MinIO Console page.

**Part 4: Deny Traffic using Network Policy**

**Step 1: Apply a Default Deny Network Policy**

Create a Network Policy to deny all ingress traffic to the MinIO pods by default.

| apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1kind: NetworkPolicymetadata:  name: deny-all  namespace: minio-networkspec:  podSelector: {}  policyTypes:  \- Ingress |
| :---- |

**Apply the network policy**

| kubectl apply \-f .\\minio\_denyall\_policy.yaml |
| :---- |

**Step 2: Let’s Verify again, Access to MinIO from the Test Pod**:

| kubectl exec \-it test\-pod \-n test\-namespace \-- curl \-u admin:password  http://minio-service.minio-network.svc.cluster.local:9001 |
| :---- |

This time you will notice that test-pod is not able to connect to MinIO pod and connection will time out,

**Part 5:  Allow Traffic from a Specific Pod**

Create a Network Policy to allow traffic only from a specific pod that acts as an application accessing MinIO (e.g., a client pod).

**Step1: Network policy to allow pod with specific labels** 

Apply a network policy to allow pod with matching labels as app=client .YAML can be found at location (`Kubernetes_Admins\labs\Lab8\allow_client.yaml`)

| apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1kind: NetworkPolicymetadata:  name: allow-client  namespace: minio-networkspec:  podSelector:    matchLabels:      app: minio  policyTypes:  \- Ingress  ingress:  \- from:    \- namespaceSelector:        matchLabels:          name: test-namespace    \- podSelector:        matchLabels:          app: client    ports:    \- protocol: TCP      port: 9001    \- protocol: TCP      port: 9000 |
| :---- |

**Step 2: Let’s Verify again, Access to MinIO from the Test Pod**:

| kubectl exec \-it test\-pod \-n test\-namespace \-- curl \-u admin:password  http://minio-service.minio-network.svc.cluster.local:9001 |
| :---- |

Please note that minikube is not working with network policies well.

**END OF LAB**
